{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280604926/1949032001/0325.xml":{"full_text":"Editorials\u2014Features\u2014Stamps\nResorts and Travel\n$fjc gmnttaij ftaf\nBooks\u2014Theaters\u2014Radio\nMusic\u2014Art\nTEN PAGES\nWASHINGTON, D. C\u201e MARCH 20, 1949\nBritish to Urge Defense\nOn Commonwealth Basis\nInroads of Communism Pose Too Great a\nThreat for New Sovereign Nations so\nLondon Proposes New Coalition\nBy Constantine Brown\nUnited we stand, divided we fall. This is the slogan which\nemissaries from the United Kingdom are taking to the countries of\nthe British Commonwealth In the Indian Ocean area.\nA \u201ctask force\u201d of high officials from London is going to make\na long trip to discuss with the chiefs of the commonwealth countries\nthe matter of common defense against the growing encroachments\nof the Soviet Union in a part of\nthe world whose importance can\nnot be overestimated, because it\ncontains basic raw materials.\nThese officials will carry with\nthem the message that unless the\nnations which once comprised the\nBritish Empire stick together they\nwill risk losing everything they\nhave gained.\nIndia, of course, is the key to\nthe edifice of the commonwealth:\nIt is to that country that the\npersuasive efforts of the British\nspokesmen will be directed. Hav\ning just obtained independence,\nthe Indian people and their gov\nernment naturally are jealous pf\ntheir new-won sovereignty and\nreluctant to agree to anything\nthat could be regarded, even by\nImplication, as interference with\ntheir rights.\nCommunist Alarm\nHowever. Prime Minister Jawa\nharlal Nehru already has become\nconcerned over the activities of\nthe Communists in his country.\nThe numerically unimportant\nCommunist Party has adopted the\ngame methods employed by Com\nmunists in other parts of the\nworld to impose their will.\nThey have infiltrated the labor\nunions, which are too young and\ntoo unsure of themselves to play\nproperly their essential role in\nthe national life.. In the Indian\nsubcontinent and in other parts\nof the South Pacific and Indian\nOcean areas\u2014Indo-China, Ma\nlaya, Burma, Indonesia, Siam and\nChina itself\u2014the labor unions are\nutilized by the Soviets for their\nown end, which is the creation of\nchaos and confusion.\nThe activities of Communist\nagents in the Far East have been\nmore carefully watched by the\nBritish than by ourselves. Nobody\nin Britain fell for the myth, ac\ncepted by so many high officials\nof the United States, that the\nChinese Communists were nothing\nbut agrarian reformers who had\nnothing but a tenuous ideological\ntie with Moscow.\nWhile we glossed over the\nviolent outbursts in Indo-China.\nMalaya, Burma and Indonesia as\nthe inevitable \u201cgrowing pains\u2019\u2019 of\nnew countries, or regarded them\nas the effects of British. French\nand Dutch imperialisms, Western\nEuropeans realized that they were\nthe evidence of Russia\u2019s intrigue\nIn those vast areas, which was the\nresult of a definite plan formu\nlated by the Politburo in Moscow.\nAim is Disaster\nThe U. S. S. R., trained veteran\nobservers of world politics say,\ndoes not aim actually to incor\nporate the Far East into the Soviet\nsystem, but it does aim to organise\nthe Asiatics into one or several\ngroups wholly sympathetic with\nand subject to Moscow\u2019s domina\ntion.\nFor the present, schemers in the\nKremlin plan only to create chaos\nthroughout Asiatic areas. The\nmen of the Politburo have\nno constructive policy regarding\nAsia, as they do with respect to\nGermany and the satellite states.\nThe only purpose they have is to\ncreate disaster by means of civil\natrife, sabotage and'other devices\nof social and political obstruction.\nTheir aim is to deprive the West\nof strategic materials rubber,\nbauxite, oil, etc.\u2014which are de\nveloped In abundant quantities in\nAsiatic areas.\nThis explains the present hope\nless guerrilla warfare which rages\nIn Malaya and Burma, as well as\nthe activities of Moscow-trained\nnatives in Indonesia and the Phil\nippines.\nBecause American attention is\nfocused on the intensified cold\nwar in Europe, we pay little if any\nattention to the drama across the\nPacific. We have only sketchy\nreports about battles which have\nbeen going on in Malaya for nearly\na year and which have become so\nsevere that the British had to\nsend reinforcements to cope with\nthe Russian trained guerrilla\nleaders in the Malay Peninsula.\nDutch Clamp Down\nSeldom do we hear about the\nbloody encounters which occur\nfrequently throughout India,\nwhere Communist agents, infiltrat\ned through the young Indian la\nbor unions, are promoting strikes\nostensibly to improve the lot of\nthe Indian workmen, but actually\nfor the purpose of precipitating\narmed conflicts with the author\nities.\nThe bulk of American citizens\nshowed undisguised indignation\nlast December when the Nether\nlands government, aware that\nCommunists who had bored into\nthe Indonesian Republican gov\nernment were attempting to make\nit the tool of Moscow, clamped\n\u2022down on that effort.\nAmericans were moved by hon\nest ideologies when we became\nangered at the \u2018\u2018reactionary and\nhigh-handed methods\u201d of the\nDutch government and failed to\nunderstand that their actions were\nprompted less by the desire to\nkeep Indonesia for exploitation\nthan by the fear that a successful\ncoup would be fatal to the defense\nplans of the Western powers. Be\ncause the Western world is so con\ncerned over Moscow\u2019s charges of\njingoism, it would not reveal the\nreal reason for the Dutch actions,\nwjiich was the safeguarding of a\nterritory which is full of essential\nraw materials.\nThe whole Par East is seething\ntoday, the members of our diplo\nmatic and economic missions re\nport to Washington. The unrest\nhas been greatly accentuated by\nthe collapse of the Nanking gov\nernment and spectacular success\nof the Communist armies in China.\nThe Asiatics were fully confident\nthat Chiang Kai-shek would be\nable to hold his own. since they\nwere convinced that the United\nStates was behind him.\nU. S. Loses Face\nThe Asiatics do not know, of\ncourse, the inside of our politics\nin regard to China and the con\nviction of our ideologists that we\nshould not support the corrupt\nKoumUitang government against\nmere \u201cagrarian reformers,\u201d as\nMao Tse-tung and his followers\nwere described.\nAll they know now\u2014and Soviet\nagents are exploiting this for all\nit is worth\u2014is that the great\nUnited States had to give up be\nfore the might of the U. S. S. R.j\nChiang lost face and was forced\ninto retirement. America lost face,\ntoo, and the destructive work of\nthe Soviet propagandists\u2014the work\nof an almost infinitessimal minor\nity over nearly a billion persons\u2014\nnow is going on throughout Asia\nat top speed.\nIn the years preceding Pearl\nHarbor the Japanese attempted to\nwin that vast population to their\nside. They could offer only cheap,\nshoddy manufactured goods in\ncompetition with the more expen\nsive British wares. Russia has\nnone of these to offer. But she\nhas something better. That is the\npromise of a happy and luxurious\nlife for those who place themselves\nin her service as \"leaders,\u201d and\nhas other promises for the future\nof the masses.\nThese have been far more suc\ncessful than the activities of the\nJapanese. The war for independ\nence conducted by the Viet Namese\nin Indo-rChina has continued un\nabated for more than two years\nand is draining France of her best\nmanpower. It also is making\nheavy inroads in the French\ntreasury.\nBritish Take a Hand\nIn Burma the Communists have\ntaken Mandalay, and the new\ngovernment at Rangoon is fight\ning with its back to the wall\nagainst insurgents who are led, as\nother Asiatics are led, by Moscow\ntrained men.\nIn India the\u2019 efforts of the gov\nernment to organize that vast\ncountry of more than 200,000,000\npersons is being seriously handi\ncapped by the activities of Com\nmunists.\nThe British government, which\nseems to have decided that the\nchances of getting along with\nRussia are extremely small, now\nis sending its spokesmen to the\ncountries which used to form its\nempire. It is discussing the ques\ntion of common defense with the\nmen who rule the destinies of\nthose new soverign nations.\nThere is no question of inter\nfering with their sovereignty. It\nis merely an endeavor to line up\nthe former component parts of the\nempire in a plan of self-defense in\nco-operation with the Western\nworld. It is a question of corre\nlating activities to plan for the\nmaintenance of a defensive coali\ntion between Occident and Orient\nand to drive home to the leaders\nof those countries the fact that\ntheir newly acquired independence\nwill be short lived unless there is\na co-operative plan for the com\nmon defense.\nAustralia, which in the past\nconsidered the potential Red\nmenace as a bugaboo of old-fash\nioned imperalists, has begun to\nrealize that its own government\nand institutions now are being\nmenaced. It is taking steps to\nprevent further Communist in\nroads into that country.\nLast October, at a common\n\u2022wealth meeting, some steps were\ndecided on to further the defense\nof that group of nations. The\nthreat to world peace, which Lon\ndon seems to consider more real\nthan Washington does, has com\npelled the British government to\ndecide to send official emissaries\nto put into effect measures de\ncided on at that time.\nAqaba's Strategic Value an Old Story\nTender Spot in Effort\nto Establish Peace\nin Middle East\n0\nBy N. Martin Ekserdjian\n(Former Colonel, British Army, Assigned to\nPort Development ot Aqaba, 1941-1943)\nA 10-mile stretch of desert\nbeach, strategic area in two World\nWars, although far distant from\nmost of the combat operations\nof those wars, is once again a\ntender spot in efforts to maintain,\nor to re-establish, peace in the\nMiddle East.\nIt is the head of the Gulf of\nAqaba, point of junction today\nof the frontiers of four jealously\nnationalistic Middle East States\u2014\nEgypt, Israel, Trans-Jordania and\nSaudi Arabia. One of these\nstates, Israel, has troops today at\nUmm Resh Resh, a port site, while\na few miles away at the existing\nport of Aqaba is an alerted gar\nrison of British troops, bound by\ntreaty to alliance with Trans\nJordania.\nAqaba\u2019s Early History\nThe little fishing village of\nAqaba first came into contact with\nmodern civilizataon when Anglo\nFrench naval bombardment re\nduced most of it to rubble in the\nsummer of 1917. Shortly after,\non the 6th of July, it fell to Law\nrence and his Arab Irregulars as\nthey thrust down toward it from\ntheir victory at Ain Abu el Lasan.\nThe strategic significance of Aqaba\nwas then emphasized by the fact\nthat its capture, by shortening\nLawrence\u2019s lines of communication\nto the sea, opened up the Levant\nto the Allied forces.\nIn 1917 British troops came to\nAqaba for the first time to develop\na temporary military base from\nwhich the Arabs under Lawrence\nand Feisal could operate east of\nthe Jordan as Allenby\u2019s right flank.\n\u201cVessels steamed up the Gulf of\nAqaba there came the armored\ncars Egyptian laborers and\nthousands of troops\u201d (T. E.\nLawrence, \u201cSeven Pillars of Wis\ndom,\u201d chapter LX).\nThe British, who had left it 20\nyears before, came to Aqaba for\nthe second time, in 1941. There\nwas then little obvious trace of\ntheir previous visit, except that\nthe flag flying over the little Arab\nLegion Fort was the Hashimite\nj flag of Trans-Jordania, and neither\nthe star and crescent of Turkey\nnor the flag of Saudi Arabia.\nThrough most of the interwar\nperiod Trans-Jordania's southeast\njern frontier was the scene of\nskirmishes and raids which some\ntimes developed to the scale of\nquite serious affrays because Ibn\nSaud, after ousting Abdulla's\nfather, King Hussein, from .the\nHejaz, claimed Southern Trans\nJordania, including Aqaba and\nMa\u2019an, for himself. In fact, rela\ntions between the two countries\nremained unfriendly until in 1948\nthe two kings ceremoniously ex\nchanged gifts and proclaimed a\nnew friendship.\nHas an African Air\nIt was again the importance of\nAqaba as a gateway to the sea that\nbrought the British there in 1941.\nThe Luftwaffe was by then estab\nlished in the Aegean and in the\nWestern Desert of Egypt. They\nwere pounding Suez and the canal\nmercilessly in nightly raids. New\nports, lower down the Red Sea,\nhad to be developed as alternatives\nto Suez. On the eastern side of\nthe Red Sea Aqaba was the only\npossible place.\nAs the British saw it in 1941,\nits fringe of tall date palms gave\nAqaba an African air. At close\nquarters, however, it was a typical\nArab village of crowded mud brick\nhouses devoid of any attempt at\ndecoration. The dust spurting at\ntheir feet seemed to those British\nsoldiers to be the only sign of\nlife. In the center of the village\nby a little stone jetty was the\nArab Legion Fort, and behind it\nlay the ruins of its Turkish pred\necessor. Even the little Arab\nurchins were listless and so un\nsophisticated that they did not\ngreet military uniforms with\ncries of \u201cbacksheesh.\" It was\nnot surprising that in the airless,\nglaring heat of a summer\u2019s day\nonly.the British were astir.\nTheir activity bore fruit and\nsoon there was a port with good\nlighter jetties, big warehouses, a\nlight railway, utilities (including\nprecious water), accommodation\nand all the hundred and one re\nquirements for the expeditious\nhandling of 1,000-2,000 tons of\nmilitary stores daily.\nRehearsal for Invasion\nA port alone is not enough\nwithout adequate inland com\nmunications. Accordingly, the\nmeter-gauge Hejaz railway was\nextended to the edge of Naqb el\nAshtar. At the top of the Naqb\nthe high plateau of Ma\u2019an comes\nto an abrupt end and there is\na sheer drop of some 3,000 feet\nto the Plain of Gueira. The rail\nway could not be taken down this\nThese three unidentified men are shoicn in front of the mud brick house that serves the\nBritish as a hotel in the strategically important gulf port of Aqaba. \u2014AP Photo and Map.\nTRANS- ;\\<f V'\nV Naqb el Ashlar\ni P^VPmUAqaba f\nUmm Resh Resh|r^.*\nGu/fof &cu\u00ab of s S4ub/ Arabia\nKfGVTM^^wS\u00ae> M.0 .00\n,f ?V Re<* Seo j. STATUTE MILES\nprecipice, but an all-weather road\nwas blasted down its side and\nthen continued across the plain\nand through the Wadi Ithm to\nAqaba. The supplies landed in\nAqaba could thus move by truck\nconvoys to railhead and thence\nto Haifa, Damascus and Beirut.\nWhen in 1942 the German tide\nrolled back from its high-water\nmark at Alamein, the newly com\npleted port of Aqaba became\nunnecessary. Before leaving it\nfor the second time, however, the\nBritish army arranged an impres\nsive finale.\nIn the spring of 1943 the\ncode word \"Bromyard\u201d was whis\npered in military circles in the\nMiddle East.\nAn Indian brigade arrived in\nAqaba and began constructing\ndefense works and disposing them\nselves to repel seaborne invasion.\nStaff officers of various kinds\nabounded, the cinema was opened\nand the ice factory began to\noperate. The local Arabs, puzzled\nby these preparations, realized\nthat things were working up to a\ncrescendo when the brass got so\nthick on the ground that mere\nmajor generals became nearly\nas common as the torpid flies\nfor which Aqaba is notorious.\nJust before dawn one day the\nfun began: Under cover of an\nartillery barrage and air bom\n\"becalmed\nCopyright, 1949, 4} Arrongomont With London tvoning Standord\n'bardment, the British 8tli Army's'\nspearhead of some 25,000 troops\ncrashed ashore. Bangalore tor\npedoes blasted gaps in the\nbeach defenses and small-arms\nfire added its staccato note to the\ngeneral inferno of noise, smoke\nand flame. By evening the out\nnumbered defense had been over\nwhelmed and exercise \"Bromyard\u201d\nwas over. The brass pronounced!\nitself satisfied with the dress\nrehearsal and within a few days\nthe same troops\u2014with the United\nStates 7th Army alongside them\u2014\nwere landing in Sicily. This time\nthe casualties were inflicted by\nthe enemy, not by the umpires.\nReason for Being There\nAfter 1943, World War II lost\ninterest in Aqaba and, as they\nhad done a quarter of a century\nbefore, the British withdrew for\nthe second time. Only the village\nlife continued; the solidly built\nnew military town was deserted\nand so were the police hutments\nthat represented Umm Resh Resh\non the map. The truck convoys\ncarried away the military stores\nand, while some ran to railhead\nat Naqb el Ashtar, others crossed\nthe valley and at Umm Resh Resh\nbegan the dangerous ascent of the\nprecipitous gradients of the Naqb\nel Aqaba. How many of those\ndrivers realized, when they paused\nat the top of the 1,500-foot escarp\nment to cool their boiling radi\nators, that they were following in\nthe path of Balkis, Queen of\nSheba? From her kingdom in the\nsouth of Arabia she had landed\nat Solomon\u2019s port of Ezion Geber\n(where Umm Resh Resh now\nstands) en route for Jerusalem.\nEven then this precious access to\nthe sea was divided between two\nkingdoms.\nThe formal reason for British\ntroops being in Aqaba for the\nthird time is the treaty of alli\nance between Great Britain and\nTrans-Jordan signed in Amman\non March 15. 1948. Article 3 of\nthe treaty provides that the two\nparties shall assist each other not\nonly \u201cimmediately as a meas\nure of collective defense\u201d in the\nevent of war, but also in the event\nof \u201cimmediate menace of hostili\nties.\u201d Although the \u201cmenace of\nhostilities\u201d has existed for some\ntime, it was not until the vic\ntorious Israeli advance into the\nNegeb that the possibility of an\ninvasion of Trans-Jordan terri\ntory became acute. It is possible,\nmoreover, that the arrival of Brit\nish troops in Aqaba forestalled not\n4\n\u25baonly a hostile Israeli invasion.\nIbn Saud might well have sent\ntroops in to the aid of his Arab\nLeague ally and new-found friend,\nAbdullah. In view of Ibn Saud\u2019s\nlong-standing claims to Malan\nand Aqaba, these allied troops\nmight have been difficult to get\nrid of, whereas in Aqaba the Brit\nish have an excellent record of\nleaving before outstaying their\nwelcome.\nFor modem Israel, as for King\nSolomon, the Gulf of Aqaba is an\noutlet to the east. Furthermore,\nit can be developed as an outlet\nfor the valuable chemical products\nof the Dead Sea, which now have\nto go to Haifa by the arduous\nroute through Jerusalem. For the\nBritish Aqaba is on the flank of\nthe still vital Suez highway to\nthe east.\nFor Trans-Jordan an access to\nthe Red Sea is now essential. The\nHashimite kingdom\u2019s neighbors,\nwith the exception of Iraq, are\nnot friendly to Abdullah. De\nprived now of the use of Haifat\nTrans-Jordan would soon be\nstrangled.\nApart, however, from Britain\u2019s\nformal treaty obligations to\nTrans-Jordania, Britain\u2019s greatest\ninterest\u2014and not only Britain\u2019s\u2014\nis still the maintenance of peace.\nIf the presence of British troops\nsucceeds in preventing a fresh\nclash between Israel and Trans\nJordania and deters Ibn Saud\nfrom fishing in troubled waters,\nthe much criticized British ac\ntion will have been of benefit to\nall the peace-loving powers. More\nover, when they see that Western\ntreaty promises can be depended\non, the Middle Eastern states\nwill not be encouraged to seek\nfriends \u2014and protectors\u2014else\nwhere.\nIf, as part of the final peace\nsettlement, Israel receives the'\nwhole of the Palestinian Negeb,\nshe will have in Umm Resh Resh\na valuable outlet to the Red Sea\nwhich can develop alongside\nAqaba to the advantage of both;\nas in Solomon\u2019s day, so now also,\nthere is room for two ports at the\nhead of the Gulf of Aqaba. This\npeaceful development cannot,\nhowever, follow after bitter fight\ning. The present frontiers at the\nhead of the gulf are the legacy\nof Britain\u2019s first visit to Aqaba.\nThe serviceable little port, and its\ninland communications derive\nfrom the second visit. The third\nvisit can bring the most valuable\ngift of all\u2014peace.\n\nTruman and 81st Congress\nRepeating Antics of 1946\n79th Session Administered Similar Rebuff\non Social Security and Taxation;\nCoalition Still Controls\nBy Gould Lincoln\nPresident Truman is beginning to find himself right back where\nhe was three years ago\u2014when he had another Democratic Congress\non his hands\u2014the 79th. His program of legislation and spending on\nthe part of the Federal Government is practically the same as that\nwhich he submitted to the earlier Congress\u2014a program which he was\nunable to put through. Main differences in the Truman program\ntoday and three years ago he in*\nthe greater appropriations for\nforeign recovery, and in the fact\nthat the President is now trying\nto repeal the Taft-Hartley labor\nlaw, enacted by the Republican\n80th Congress.\nMr. Truman failed in his deal\ning with the 79th Congress\u2014just\nas he is apparently failing in his\ndealings with the 81st Congress.\nWhen he entered the White House\nin 1945. after President Franklin\nD. Roosevelt\u2019s death, it was with\nthe good wishes of Republicans\nand Democrats alike. It was not\nlong, however, before things began\nto bog down. By November, 1946,\nMr. Truman and the Democratic\nCongress were both unpopular, so\nmuch so that the Republicans won\nboth houses of Congress in the\nelection.\nThe President came to the 81st\nCongress in January flushed with;\nthe success of an unexpected vic\ntory at the polls in the previous\nNovember. He laid his program\nbefore the Congress, claiming he\nhad a mandate from the people\nto put it through. Uf> to date,\u2019\nnone of his program has been put\nthrough. On the other hand, he\nhas been rebuffed by Congress on\na number of occasions.\nAll Pledges Blocked\nHis pledge to put through civil\nrights legislation has been blocked\n\u2014at least temporarily. His prom\nise to rush through a repeal of\nthe Taft-Hartley labor law has\nnot materialized, although the\nCongress has been in session for\nabout two months and a half.\nHis demand that rent control\u2014\nby the Federal Government\u2014be\nextended for another two years\nand strengthened, has been turned\ndown by the House and probably\nwill meet a similar fate in the\nSenate. The final rent control\n\u201c'extension, if and when it comes,\nwill be a considerably watered\ndown variety.\nAnother demand by Mr. Tru\nman was for a price and wage\ncontrol law. It has gotten exactly\nnowhere, and its prospects are so\ndim as to be negligible. Nor has\nanything yet been done about\npublic housing or socialized medi\ncine. If and when anything is\ndone in regard to the latter two,\nthey will not be the administra\ntion\u2019s proposals.\nThe President also asked Con\ngress for an increase of $4,000,\n000,000 in taxes. The Democratic\ncommittees of the House and Sen\nate have sidetracked this request\nuntil more is learned about the\nspending program\u2014the appropria\ntions that Congress makes\u2014and\nabout economic conditions in the\ncountry. Tiie Republicans, on the\nother hand, have rallied behind a\nbill to further reduce taxes\u2014this\ntime the excise taxes, which are\nreally sales taxes on a large num\nber of goods and services.\nParty Out of Control\nIt may well be asked\u2014what\u2019s\nMr. Truman's trouble? And an\nother question\u2014dees Mr. Truman\nor the Congress represent a ma\njority ot the people?\nIn the 79th Congress, when Mr.\nTruman entered the White House\nin 1945, the political makeup of\nthe two houses was as follows:\nSenate, 55 Democrats, 40 Repub\nlicans, 1 Progressive: House, 241\nDemocrats, 190 Republicans, 1\nProgressive, 1 American-Labor, 2\nvacancies. Take a look at the\n81st Congress as it was in Jan\nuary: Senate, 54 Democrats, 42\nRepublicans: House, 263 Demo\ncrats. 171 Republicans, 1 Ameri\ncan-Labor. The Democratic con\ntrol of both houses was certain in\nboth the 79th and 81st Congresses\n_if the Democrats stuck together.\nBut Mr. Truman has not been\nable to keep the Democrats to\ngether\u2014for the program which\nhe is demanding, a program\nj which, by the way, is dictated by\npromises made to many individual\nminority groups. Too many of\nthe Democrats in Congress have\nbeen opposed to his civil rights\nprogram, to his proposal to turn\nback the clock on labor-manage\nment legislation, and to his pro\nposal to tax the people more and\nspend more money for New Deal\nprojects.\nWhat has happened in the 81st\nCongress\u2014as it did in the 79th\nCongress\u2014has been the cementing\nof a coalition of Republican and\nconservative Democrats. Most of\nthe conservative Democrats are\nfrom the South\u2014but not all.\nOne of Mr. Truman\u2019s troubles\nhas arisen from the failure on his\npart and that of his advisers to\nestimate correctly economic\ntrends in the country. Immedi\nately after hostilities ceased in the\nlast war, they figured there would\nbe huge unemployment. Nothing\nof the kind happened and Con\ngress turned down Mr. Truman\u2019s\nrequest for hundreds of millions\nof dollars additional for unem\nployment insurance. They figured,\ntoo, that wages could be increased\nwithout an increase in prices\u2014\nand that turned out to be a mis\ntake. Mr. Truman and his ex\nperts thought, also, that tax re\nceipts would be less than they\nturned out to be\u2014by a wide mar\ngin.\n(Predictions Proved Wrong\nMr. Truman during the cam\npaign insisted that unless he were\nelected, there would be a down\nward trend in business, prices to\nthe farmers, other prices and em\nployment. Well, he was elected,\nand his prediction that there\nwould not be such trends has\nproved wrong.\nAnother criticism leveled at Mr.\nTruman Is that he has not been\ngood at making appointments to\nhigh office, but has been guided\ntoo much by his personal feelings.\nThere was a celebrated case of the\nappointment of Edwin W. Pauley,\nan oil man, to be Undersecretary\nof the Navy. He had been treas\nurer and money raiser for the\nDemocratic National Committee.\nHis nomination eventually had o\nbe withdrawn. That was in IS 13.\nToday another important appoint\nment, that of former Senator a::d\nGovernor, Mon Wallgren of Wash\nington, a great personal friend of\nMr. Truman\u2019s, to be chairman of\n(See PRESIDENT, Page C-5.t\nEconomy Ills\nNeed Antidote\nEconomists Concerned\nOver Diminishing\nBuying Power\nBy Clarke Beach\nThe Nation's top economists\nhave identified the germs which\nthey believe will ultimately cause\na major depression if antidotes\nare not developed in time.\nThe views of these men. the\nPresident's Council of Economic\nadvisers, have been -backed up\npublicly by the President and are\nwidely approved by other admin\nistration economists and officials.\nTheir general theory has not as\nyet* been broadly disputed by\nbusiness leaders and economists\noutside the Government. But the\nremedies they suggest have al\nready met violent opposition both\nin Congress and among business\nmen.\nThey have recommended imme\ndiate measures which they say\nwill head off any further inflation.\nThey have' also proposed iong\nterm projects, such as a program\nto increase production capacity in\ncertain lines.\nThe council members and those\nwho support them sec little chance\nof a serious recession this year.\nThe bacteria which will eventu\nally threaten our prosperity, they\nsay. are the various maladjust\nments now developing in our econ\nomy.\nConsumer Buying Drops\nThe deadliest, as they see it, is\nthe steadily diminishing buying\npower of individual consumers.\nConsumers bought in 1948 a\nsmaller share of the Nation\u2019s\ngoods and services than ever be\nfore in a peacetime year for v/hich\nstatistics are available. Consumer\nexpenditures last year were only\n70 per cent of the national total.\nIn 1939 they were 75 per cent. In\n1929 they were 76 per cent.\nBusiness and industry account\ned for 15.4 per cent of last year's\nexpenditures investments in\nplants and facilities. This was\nwell above 1939, but approximately\nthe same as in 1,929.\nThe third category of expendi\ntures, termed \u201call others\u201d by the\ncouncil, consists almost entirely of\nGovernment spending. Most of\nthat money went for military pur\nposes and foreign aid. It account\ned for 14.7 per cent of the Nation\u2019s^\nexpenditures. This was a little\nless than 1939. But it Stood at\nonly 9 per cent in 1929.\nThus since 1929 consumer ex\npenditures have taken a big drop\n\u2014with Government expenditures\naccounting for almost the entire\nshare that the consumer lost.\nThe crisis will come, in the\nopinion of members of the coun\ncil, when Government expendi\ntures drop drastically\u2014when and\nif foreign aid and the cold war\nend.\nKeyserling\u2019* Views\nA new reconversion could be\ncomfortably managed then if in\ndustry, which had been produc\ning 'for the Government, just\nturned to consumer production.\nBut council members think that\nfor consumers to buy the large\nnew supply, they would need high\ner wages and lower prices.\nLeon H. Keyserling, vice chair\nman of the council, recently told\nthe Congressional Joint Commit\ntee on the Economic Report that\nthe business outlook at that time\nwill be dampened by the decline\nin Government demand. Industry\nthen will not be likely to expand,\nhe said, and added:\n\u201cExperience indicates, rather,\nthat the delay of adjustment un\ntil that time would result in cur\ntailment of employment and pro\nduction, followed by disorderly\nprice breaks and a general eco\nnomic decline\u2014the spiral of de\npression.\u201d\nThe council sees no chance for\nincreasing business investment\ntaking up the slack. The ratio of\nbusiness expenditures is already as\nhigh as it should be for a healthy\neconomy, in the opinion of the\ncouncil.\nThe wages of employes have\ndropped from 65.9 per cent of the\nnational income in 1939 to 61.5 per\ncent in 1948. It is coming close\nto employes\u2019 income in the depres\nsion year of 1929, which was 58.1\nper cent. (Most students of our\neconomy, said Mr. Keyserling,\nthink that the low ratio of em\nploye compensation in 1929 helped\nbring on the depression then.)\n(Distributed br the Aeioclated Pre\u00ab*>","height":"31816","width":"22424"}}
